# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: minimum-enclosing-circle
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:minimum-enclosing-circle/1-center-problem] The **1-center problem**, also known as **minimax problem** or **minmax location problem**, is a classical combinatorial optimization problem in operations research of facilities location type.
[src:minimum-enclosing-circle/1-center-problem] There are numerous particular cases of the problem, depending on the choice of the locations both of demand points and facilities, as well as the distance function.
[src:minimum-enclosing-circle/1-center-problem] A simple special case is when the feasible locations and demand points are in the plane with Euclidean distance as transportation cost (**planar minmax Euclidean facility location problem, Euclidean 1-center problem in the plane,** etc.).
[src:minimum-enclosing-circle/1-center-problem] It is also known as the smallest circle problem.
[src:minimum-enclosing-circle/1-center-problem] Its generalization to *n*-dimensional Euclidean spaces is known as the smallest enclosing ball problem.
[src:minimum-enclosing-circle/1-center-problem] A further generalization (**weighted Euclidean facility location**) is when the set of weights is assigned to demand points and the transportation cost is the sum of the products of distances by the corresponding weights.
[src:minimum-enclosing-circle/1-center-problem] Another special case, the closest string problem, arises when the inputs are strings and their distance is measured using Hamming distance.
[src:minimum-enclosing-circle/1-center-problem] The 1-center problem can be restated as finding a star in a weighted complete graph that minimizes the maximum weight of the selected edges.
[src:minimum-enclosing-circle/1-center-problem] The corresponding problem of minimizing the maximum weight of a path between two selected vertices, in place of a star, is called the minimax path problem.
[src:minimum-enclosing-circle/bounding-sphere] In mathematics, given a non-empty set of objects of finite extension in d -dimensional space, for example a set of points, a **bounding sphere**, **enclosing sphere** or **enclosing ball** for that set is a d -dimensional solid sphere containing all of these objects.
[src:minimum-enclosing-circle/bounding-sphere] Used in computer graphics and computational geometry, a bounding sphere is a special type of bounding volume.
[src:minimum-enclosing-circle/bounding-sphere] There are several fast and simple bounding sphere construction algorithms with a high practical value in real-time computer graphics applications.
[src:minimum-enclosing-circle/bounding-sphere] In statistics and operations research, the objects are typically points, and generally the sphere of interest is the **minimal bounding sphere**, that is, the sphere with minimal radius among all bounding spheres.
[src:minimum-enclosing-circle/bounding-sphere] It may be proven that such a sphere is unique: If there are two of them, then the objects in question lie within their intersection.
[src:minimum-enclosing-circle/bounding-sphere] But an intersection of two non-coinciding spheres of equal radius is contained in a sphere of smaller radius.
[src:minimum-enclosing-circle/bounding-sphere] The problem of computing the center of a minimal bounding sphere is also known as the "unweighted Euclidean 1-center problem".
[src:minimum-enclosing-circle/bounding-sphere] Such spheres are useful in clustering, where groups of similar data points are classified together.
[src:minimum-enclosing-circle/bounding-sphere] In statistical analysis the scattering of data points within a sphere may be attributed to measurement error or natural (usually thermal) processes, in which case the cluster represents a perturbation of an ideal point.
[src:minimum-enclosing-circle/bounding-sphere] In some circumstances this ideal point may be used as a substitute for the points in the cluster, advantageous in reducing calculation time.
[src:minimum-enclosing-circle/bounding-sphere] In operations research the clustering of values to an ideal point may also be used to reduce the number of inputs in order to obtain approximate values for NP-hard problems in a reasonable time.
[src:minimum-enclosing-circle/bounding-sphere] The point chosen is not usually the center of the sphere, as this can be biased by outliers, but instead some form of average location such as a least squares point is computed to represent the cluster.
[src:minimum-enclosing-circle/bounding-sphere] There are exact and approximate algorithms for solving the bounding sphere problem.
[src:minimum-enclosing-circle/bounding-sphere] Nimrod Megiddo studied the 1-center problem extensively and published on it at least five times in the 1980s.
[src:minimum-enclosing-circle/bounding-sphere] In 1983, he proposed a "prune and search" algorithm which finds the optimum bounding sphere and runs in linear time if the dimension is fixed as a constant.
[src:minimum-enclosing-circle/bounding-sphere] When the dimension d is taken into account, the execution time complexity is $O(2^{O(d^{2})}n)$ , which is impractical for high-dimensional applications.
[src:minimum-enclosing-circle/bounding-sphere] In 1991, Emo Welzl proposed a much simpler randomized algorithm, generalizing a randomized linear programming algorithm by Raimund Seidel.
[src:minimum-enclosing-circle/bounding-sphere] The expected running time of Welzl's algorithm is $O((d+1)(d+1)!\ n)$ , which again reduces to $O(n)$ for any fixed dimension d .
[src:minimum-enclosing-circle/bounding-sphere] The paper provides experimental results demonstrating its practicality in higher dimensions.
[src:minimum-enclosing-circle/bounding-sphere] A more recent deterministic algorithm of Timothy Chan runs in $O(d^{\left({\frac {1}{2}}+o(1)\right)d}n)$ , again reducing to $O(n)$ time with fixed dimension, with a smaller, but still exponential, dependence on the dimension.
[src:minimum-enclosing-circle/bounding-sphere] The open-source Computational Geometry Algorithms Library (CGAL) contains an implementation of Welzl's algorithm.
[src:minimum-enclosing-circle/bounding-sphere] The smallest enclosing sphere of a finite point set can also be computed using convex optimization, specifically second-order cone programming (SOCP).
[src:minimum-enclosing-circle/bounding-sphere] This approach formulates the problem as minimizing the radius of a sphere subject to second-order (quadratic) constraints that require each point to lie within or on the sphere.
[src:minimum-enclosing-circle/bounding-sphere] where the center *c* and radius *r* are the optimization variables, and *x*i are the input points.
[src:minimum-enclosing-circle/bounding-sphere] This formulation defines a convex optimization problem that can be solved efficiently using modern interior-point methods and SOCP solvers.
[src:minimum-enclosing-circle/bounding-sphere] While this approach provides an exact mathematical formulation, the solution is typically computed to high numerical accuracy rather than exact machine precision.
[src:minimum-enclosing-circle/bounding-sphere] As such, it offers a practical alternative to geometric algorithms, especially in higher dimensions or when integrating with other optimization-based methods.
[src:minimum-enclosing-circle/bounding-sphere] This convex formulation is discussed in sources such as Boyd & Vandenberghe's convex optimization book, and is widely supported in convex optimization software such as CVX, CVXPY, and MOSEK.
[src:minimum-enclosing-circle/bounding-sphere] In 1990, Jack Ritter proposed a simple algorithm to find a non-minimal bounding sphere.
[src:minimum-enclosing-circle/bounding-sphere] It is widely used in various applications for its simplicity.
[src:minimum-enclosing-circle/bounding-sphere] Search a point z in P , which has the largest distance from y .
[src:minimum-enclosing-circle/bounding-sphere] If all points in P are within ball B , then we get a bounding sphere.
[src:minimum-enclosing-circle/bounding-sphere] Otherwise, let p be a point outside the ball, constructs a new ball covering both point p and previous ball.
[src:minimum-enclosing-circle/bounding-sphere] Repeat this step until all points are covered.
[src:minimum-enclosing-circle/bounding-sphere] Ritter's algorithm runs in time $O(nd)$ on inputs consisting of n points in d -dimensional space, which makes it very efficient.
[src:minimum-enclosing-circle/bounding-sphere] However, it gives only a coarse result which is usually 5% to 20% larger than the optimum.
[src:minimum-enclosing-circle/bounding-sphere] Bădoiu et al. presented a $1+\varepsilon$ approximation to the bounding sphere problem, where a $1+\varepsilon$ approximation means that the constructed sphere has radius at most $(1+\varepsilon )r$ , where r is the smallest possible radius of a bounding sphere.
[src:minimum-enclosing-circle/bounding-sphere] A coreset is a small subset, that a $1+\varepsilon$ expansion of the solution on the subset is a bounding sphere of the whole set.
[src:minimum-enclosing-circle/bounding-sphere] The coreset is constructed incrementally by adding the farthest point into the set in each iteration.
[src:minimum-enclosing-circle/bounding-sphere] Kumar et al. improved this approximation algorithm so that it runs in time $O({\frac {nd}{\epsilon }}+{\frac {1}{\epsilon ^{4.5}}}\log {\frac {1}{\epsilon }})$ .
[src:minimum-enclosing-circle/bounding-sphere] (2003) proposed an exact solver, though the algorithm does not have a polynomial running time in the worst case.
[src:minimum-enclosing-circle/bounding-sphere] The algorithm is purely combinatorial and implements a pivoting scheme similar to the simplex method for linear programming, used earlier in some heuristics.
[src:minimum-enclosing-circle/bounding-sphere] It starts with a large sphere that covers all points and gradually shrinks it until it cannot be shrunk further.
[src:minimum-enclosing-circle/bounding-sphere] The algorithm features correct termination rules in cases of degeneracies, overlooked by prior authors; and efficient handling of partial solutions, which produces a major speed-up.
[src:minimum-enclosing-circle/bounding-sphere] The authors verified that the algorithm is efficient in practice in low and moderately low (up to 10,000) dimensions and claim it does not exhibit numerical stability problems in its floating-point operations.
[src:minimum-enclosing-circle/bounding-sphere] A C++ implementation of the algorithm is available as an open-source project.
[src:minimum-enclosing-circle/bounding-sphere] Larsson (2008) proposed the "extremal points optimal sphere" method with controllable speed to accuracy approximation to solve the bounding sphere problem.
[src:minimum-enclosing-circle/bounding-sphere] This method works by taking a set of s direction vectors and projecting all points onto each vector in s ; s serves as a speed-accuracy trade-off variable.
[src:minimum-enclosing-circle/bounding-sphere] An exact solver is applied to the $2s$ extremal points of these projections.
[src:minimum-enclosing-circle/bounding-sphere] The algorithm then iterates over the remaining points, if any, growing the sphere if necessary.
[src:minimum-enclosing-circle/bounding-sphere] For large n this method is orders of magnitude faster than exact methods, while giving comparable results.
[src:minimum-enclosing-circle/chebyshev-center] In geometry, the **Chebyshev center** of a bounded set Q having non-empty interior is the center of the minimal-radius ball enclosing the entire set Q , or alternatively (and non-equivalently) the center of largest inscribed ball of Q .
[src:minimum-enclosing-circle/chebyshev-center] In the field of parameter estimation, the Chebyshev center approach tries to find an estimator ${\hat {x}}$ for x given the feasibility set Q , such that ${\hat {x}}$ minimizes the worst possible estimation error for x (e.g. best worst case).
[src:minimum-enclosing-circle/chebyshev-center] There exist several alternative representations for the Chebyshev center.
[src:minimum-enclosing-circle/chebyshev-center] Despite these properties, finding the Chebyshev center may be a hard numerical optimization problem.
[src:minimum-enclosing-circle/chebyshev-center] For example, in the second representation above, the inner maximization is non-convex if the set *Q* is not convex.
[src:minimum-enclosing-circle/chebyshev-center] In inner product spaces and two-dimensional spaces, if Q is closed, bounded and convex, then the Chebyshev center is in Q .
[src:minimum-enclosing-circle/chebyshev-center] In other words, the search for the Chebyshev center can be conducted inside Q without loss of generality.
[src:minimum-enclosing-circle/chebyshev-center] In other spaces, the Chebyshev center may not be in Q , even if Q is convex.
[src:minimum-enclosing-circle/chebyshev-center] Consider the case in which the set Q can be represented as the intersection of k ellipsoids.
[src:minimum-enclosing-circle/chebyshev-center] This last **convex** optimization problem is known as the **relaxed Chebyshev center** (RCC).
[src:minimum-enclosing-circle/chebyshev-center] It can be shown that the well-known constrained least squares (CLS) problem is a relaxed version of the Chebyshev center.
[src:minimum-enclosing-circle/chebyshev-center] One can see that this problem is a relaxation of the Chebyshev center (though different than the RCC described above).
[src:minimum-enclosing-circle/chebyshev-center] A solution set $(x,\Delta )$ for the RCC is also a solution for the CLS, and thus $T\in V$ .
[src:minimum-enclosing-circle/chebyshev-center] This means that the CLS estimate is the solution of a looser relaxation than that of the RCC.
[src:minimum-enclosing-circle/chebyshev-center] Hence the **CLS is an upper bound for the RCC**, which is an upper bound for the real Chebyshev center.
[src:minimum-enclosing-circle/chebyshev-center] Since both the RCC and CLS are based upon relaxation of the real feasibility set Q , the form in which Q is defined affects its relaxed versions.
[src:minimum-enclosing-circle/chebyshev-center] This of course affects the quality of the RCC and CLS estimators.
[src:minimum-enclosing-circle/chebyshev-center] It turns out that the first representation results with an upper bound estimator for the second one, hence using it may dramatically decrease the quality of the calculated estimator.
[src:minimum-enclosing-circle/chebyshev-center] This simple example shows us that great care should be given to the formulation of constraints when relaxation of the feasibility region is used.
[src:minimum-enclosing-circle/chebyshev-center] This problem can be formulated as a linear programming problem, provided that the region Q is an intersection of finitely many hyperplanes.
[src:minimum-enclosing-circle/chebyshev-center] Given a polytope, Q, defined as follows then it can be solved via the following linear program.
[src:minimum-enclosing-circle/minimum-bounding-box] When other kinds of measure are used, the minimum box is usually called accordingly, e.g., "minimum-perimeter bounding box".
[src:minimum-enclosing-circle/minimum-bounding-box] The minimum bounding box of a point set is the same as the minimum bounding box of its convex hull, a fact which may be used heuristically to speed up computation.
[src:minimum-enclosing-circle/minimum-bounding-box] In the two-dimensional case it is called the *minimum bounding rectangle*.
[src:minimum-enclosing-circle/minimum-bounding-box] The axis-aligned minimum bounding box (or **AABB**) for a given point set is its minimum bounding box subject to the constraint that the edges of the box are parallel to the (Cartesian) coordinate axes.
[src:minimum-enclosing-circle/minimum-bounding-box] It is the Cartesian product of *N* intervals each of which is defined by the minimal and maximal value of the corresponding coordinate for the points in *S*.
[src:minimum-enclosing-circle/minimum-bounding-box] Axis-aligned minimal bounding boxes are used as an approximate location of an object in question and as a very simple descriptor of its shape.
[src:minimum-enclosing-circle/minimum-bounding-box] For example, in computational geometry and its applications when it is required to find intersections in the set of objects, the initial check is the intersections between their MBBs.
[src:minimum-enclosing-circle/minimum-bounding-box] Since it is usually a much less expensive operation than the check of the actual intersection (because it only requires comparisons of coordinates), it allows quickly excluding checks of the pairs that are far apart.
[src:minimum-enclosing-circle/minimum-bounding-box] The arbitrarily oriented minimum bounding box is the minimum bounding box, calculated subject to no constraints as to the orientation of the result.
[src:minimum-enclosing-circle/minimum-bounding-box] A three-dimensional rotating calipers algorithm can find the minimum-volume arbitrarily-oriented bounding box of a three-dimensional point set in cubic time.
[src:minimum-enclosing-circle/minimum-bounding-box] Matlab implementations of the latter as well as the optimal compromise between accuracy and CPU time are available.
[src:minimum-enclosing-circle/minimum-bounding-box] In the case where an object has its own local coordinate system, it can be useful to store a bounding box relative to these axes, which requires no transformation as the object's own transformation changes.
[src:minimum-enclosing-circle/minimum-bounding-box] In digital image processing, the *bounding box* is merely the coordinates of the rectangular border that fully encloses a digital image when it is placed over a page, a canvas, a screen or other similar bidimensional background.
[src:minimum-enclosing-circle/smallest-circle-problem] The corresponding problem in *n*-dimensional space, the smallest bounding sphere problem, is to compute the smallest *n*-sphere that contains all of a given set of points.
[src:minimum-enclosing-circle/smallest-circle-problem] The smallest-circle problem was initially proposed by the English mathematician James Joseph Sylvester in 1857.
[src:minimum-enclosing-circle/smallest-circle-problem] The smallest-circle problem in the plane is an example of a facility location problem (the 1-center problem) in which the location of a new facility must be chosen to provide service to a number of customers, minimizing the farthest distance that any customer must travel to reach the new facility.
[src:minimum-enclosing-circle/smallest-circle-problem] Both the smallest circle problem in the plane, and the smallest bounding sphere problem in any higher-dimensional space of bounded dimension are solvable in worst-case linear time.
[src:minimum-enclosing-circle/smallest-circle-problem] As Nimrod Megiddo showed, the minimum enclosing circle can be found in linear time, and the same linear time bound also applies to the smallest enclosing sphere in Euclidean spaces of any constant dimension.
[src:minimum-enclosing-circle/smallest-circle-problem] His article also gives a brief overview of earlier $O(n^{3})$ and $O(n\log n)$ algorithms; in doing so, Megiddo demonstrated that Shamos and Hoey's conjecture – that a solution to the smallest-circle problem was computable in $\Omega (n\log n)$ at best – was false.
[src:minimum-enclosing-circle/smallest-circle-problem] Emo Welzl proposed a simple randomized algorithm for the minimum covering circle problem that runs in expected time $O(n)$ , based on a linear programming algorithm of Raimund Seidel.
[src:minimum-enclosing-circle/smallest-circle-problem] Subsequently, the smallest-circle problem was included in a general class of LP-type problems that can be solved by algorithms like Welzl's based on linear programming.
[src:minimum-enclosing-circle/smallest-circle-problem] As a consequence of membership in this class, it was shown that the dependence on the dimension of the constant factor in the $O(n)$ time bound, which was factorial for Seidel's method, could be reduced to subexponential.
[src:minimum-enclosing-circle/smallest-circle-problem] Welzl's minidisk algorithm has been extended to handle Bregman divergences which include the squared Euclidean distance.
[src:minimum-enclosing-circle/smallest-circle-problem] Megiddo's algorithm is based on the technique called prune and search, reducing the size of the problem by removing ${\textstyle {\frac {n}{16}}}$ unnecessary points.
[src:minimum-enclosing-circle/smallest-circle-problem] The algorithm is rather complicated and it is reflected by its big multiplicative constant.
[src:minimum-enclosing-circle/smallest-circle-problem] The reduction needs to solve twice the similar problem where the center of the sought-after enclosing circle is constrained to lie on a given line.
[src:minimum-enclosing-circle/smallest-circle-problem] The solution of the subproblem is either the solution of the unconstrained problem or it is used to determine the half-plane where the unconstrained solution center is located.
[src:minimum-enclosing-circle/smallest-circle-problem] The ${\textstyle {\frac {n}{16}}}$ points to be discarded are found as follows: The points *Pi* are arranged into pairs which defines ${\textstyle {\frac {n}{2}}}$ lines *pj* as their bisectors.
[src:minimum-enclosing-circle/smallest-circle-problem] The line *q* in the *p*1 direction is placed to go through an intersection *Qx* such that there are ${\textstyle {\frac {n}{8}}}$ intersections in each half-plane defined by the line (median position).
[src:minimum-enclosing-circle/smallest-circle-problem] The constrained version of the enclosing problem is run on the line q' which determines the half-plane where the center is located.
[src:minimum-enclosing-circle/smallest-circle-problem] The line *q*′ in the *pm* direction is placed to go through an intersection *Qx'* such that there are ${\textstyle {\frac {n}{16}}}$ intersections in each half of the half-plane not containing the solution.
[src:minimum-enclosing-circle/smallest-circle-problem] The constrained version of the enclosing problem is run on line *q*′ which together with *q* determines the quadrant where the center is located.
[src:minimum-enclosing-circle/smallest-circle-problem] We consider the points *Qk* in the quadrant not contained in a half-plane containing the solution.
[src:minimum-enclosing-circle/smallest-circle-problem] One of the bisectors of the pair defining *Qk* has the direction ensuring which of points *Pi* defining the bisector is closer to each point in the quadrant containing the center of the enclosing circle.
[src:minimum-enclosing-circle/smallest-circle-problem] The ${\textstyle {\frac {n}{4}}}$ points to be discarded are found as follows: Points *Pi* are arranged into pairs.
[src:minimum-enclosing-circle/smallest-circle-problem] For each pair, the intersection *Qj* of its bisector with the constraining line *q* is found (If this intersection does not exist we could remove one point from the pair immediately).
[src:minimum-enclosing-circle/smallest-circle-problem] The median *M* of points *Qj* on the line *q* is found and in *O*(*n*) time is determined which halfline of *q* starting in *M* contains the solution of the constrained problem.
[src:minimum-enclosing-circle/smallest-circle-problem] We consider points *Qj* from the other half.
[src:minimum-enclosing-circle/smallest-circle-problem] We know which of the points *Pi* defining *Qj* is closer to the each point of the halfline containing center of the enclosing circle of the constrained problem solution.
[src:minimum-enclosing-circle/smallest-circle-problem] The half-plane where the unconstrained solution lies could be determined by the points *Pi* on the boundary of the constrained circle solution.
[src:minimum-enclosing-circle/smallest-circle-problem] (The first and last point on the circle in each half-plane suffice.
[src:minimum-enclosing-circle/smallest-circle-problem] The initial input is a set *P* of points.
[src:minimum-enclosing-circle/smallest-circle-problem] The algorithm selects one point *p* randomly and uniformly from *P*, and recursively finds the minimal circle containing *P* – {*p*}, i.e. all of the other points in *P* except *p*.
[src:minimum-enclosing-circle/smallest-circle-problem] If the returned circle also encloses *p*, it is the minimal circle for the whole of *P* and is returned.
[src:minimum-enclosing-circle/smallest-circle-problem] Otherwise, point *p* must lie on the boundary of the result circle.
[src:minimum-enclosing-circle/smallest-circle-problem] It recurses, but with the set *R* of points known to be on the boundary as an additional parameter.
[src:minimum-enclosing-circle/smallest-circle-problem] Recursion can also terminate when *R* has size 3 (in 2D, or 4 in 3D) because the remaining points in *P* must lie within the circle described by *R*.
[src:minimum-enclosing-circle/smallest-circle-problem] Welzl's paper states that it is sufficient to randomly permute the input at the start, rather than performing independently random choices of *p* on each recursion.
[src:minimum-enclosing-circle/smallest-circle-problem] It also states that performance is improved by dynamically re-ordering the points so that those that are found to be outside a circle are subsequently considered earlier, but this requires a change in the structure of the algorithm to store *P* as a "global".
[src:minimum-enclosing-circle/smallest-circle-problem] Prior to Megiddo's result showing that the smallest-circle problem may be solved in linear time, several algorithms of higher complexity appeared in the literature.
[src:minimum-enclosing-circle/smallest-circle-problem] A naive algorithm solves the problem in time O(*n*4) by testing the circles determined by all pairs and triples of points.
[src:minimum-enclosing-circle/smallest-circle-problem] The weighted version of the minimum covering circle problem takes as input a set of points in a Euclidean space, each with weights; the goal is to find a single point that minimizes the maximum weighted distance (i.e., distance multiplied by the corresponding weight) to any point.
[src:minimum-enclosing-circle/smallest-circle-problem] The original (unweighted) minimum covering circle problem corresponds to the case when all weights are equal to 1.
[src:minimum-enclosing-circle/smallest-circle-problem] As with the unweighted problem, the weighted problem may be solved in linear time in any space of bounded dimension, using approaches closely related to bounded dimension linear programming algorithms, although slower algorithms are again frequent in the literature.
[src:minimum-enclosing-circle/smallest-circle-problem] The smallest enclosing ball of a finite point set has been studied in Riemannian geometry including Cartan-Hadamard manifolds.
